MissionCommands.Message: {{profileName}}, T-10 minutes to launch. We are ready for external power removal. When ready, please execute the FULL INTERNAL POWER checklist.
Go through the Mission Briefing, I will reach out at T-5 minutes.
Roger.
Ok, T-5 minutes to launch. Perform the FINAL CHECKS checklist.
T-1 minute. We are GO for launch.
T-30 seconds, good luck {{profileName}}!
Lift-off! Follow the ASCENT checklist to insertion.
There goes the booster, I see a drop in the g's.
Roger. How's this rocket compared to the Redstone?
Sure feels bigger, picked up some vibrations earlier but getting real smooth now.
Tower is gone.
Roger, we see BECO. The sustainer will complete the job. Please complete the BECO checklist.
Cap Sep is green!
Roger. Once turnaround is completed, please perform the ORBIT checklist.
Roger, will complete the ORBIT checklist.
Roger. We are checking orbit data.
We are GO for orbit. Use the FBW system to manually track the launch vehicle through the window as you are heading for CYI.
Roger, FBW enabled. See you at CYI.
CYI in range. We get telemetry indicating that Battery 2 is faulty. Please verify, and if so, shut it down for now.
Roger, currently seeing 0 volts on battery 2. Will shut it down.
Battery 2 is offline. How do we proceed?
Continue as planned. We still have the two other main batteries, as well as the standby battery.
Keep an extra eye on those batteries for the rest of the mission. If another fails, we will do an early retrograde.
Roger. Will do.
Returning to the objectives. Next we will maneuver the spacecraft to prograde attitude using FBW. Verify that you are in FBW.
The craft is in FBW.
Roger, set the GYROS to FREE.
GYROS to FREE.

Using as little fuel as possible, slowly maneuver to YAW 180, and maintain prograde attitude. Maintain until ZZB. Using pitch only, pitch up and down to observe Africa as it fades from brown to green.
Roger. See you at Zanzibar (ZZB).
ZZB reads you. The Sustainer should be somewhere below you, and will move ahead of you in a lower orbit. Use the checklist to switch to MANUAL PROPULSION, and track the sustainer.
Roger. Will try to locate it and track it. See you at IOS.

IOS reads you. Complete the PRE-DARK checklist and ignore the RCS check. When complete, return to retrograde attitude. From 0,0,0, yaw left until you can observe the last remains of the sunset. See you at MUC.
Welcome to Australia! It might be hard to see anything during night, but try to observe the lights, then take a brief break. We will reach out at GYM.
Roger, sounds like a good plan. This is {{capsuleName}} signing off. Over.
Good morning! How do you feel?
Feeling good up here. Being weightless seems to have no impact on my performance.
Roger. The Flight Surgeon is analyzing the data.
Roger. All fine up here!
The Flight Surgeon wants you to take a blood test sample.
Press START on the blood test, then let it run for 30 seconds.
Thanks. In the next orbit we will perform the retrograde and return back to Earth. See you at CNV.
Welcome back to the cape, we are glad to see you, and congratulations on completing a full orbit! This is a huge achievement for the program!
Thank you. Earth sure is beautiful from this altitude.
I'm scheduled for the last Mercury mission, looking forward to getting into orbit.
Let us prepare the attitude. Set the GYRO to NORMAL.
Manually return the craft to retrograde attitude (0,0,0). Press ROGER when complete.
Complete the FLIGHT MODES > NORMAL MODE (ASCS AUTO) checklist to configure the craft for ASCS auto.
Roger, will complete the checklist.
Okay, ASCS is AUTO.
We are 30 minutes from retrograde. Prepare the cockpit by following the T-30 minutes part of the PRE-RETRO checklist - cooling the cockpit interior before entry.
T-15 minutes to Retrograde Sequence Initiation. Complete the PRE-RETRO checklist.
Retro sequence starting - waiting for ignition. Verify that the capsule is ready, and follow the RETRO checklist.
Ignition! RETRO checklist.
Roger, retros are firing!
Prepare for jettison by following the REENTRY checklist. We will soon re-enter.
RETRO JETTISON is green!
Roger, we see the same. Excellent. Prepare for entry interface.
0.05g detected, entry interface started.
Roger. Verify reentry attitude, and that the ASCS is working. Prepare to take over manual control during entry as needed. We will see you on the inside of the atmosphere. Enjoy the ride!
G's building up.
This is {{capsuleName}}, do you read?
This is {{capsuleName}}, do you read?
Loud and clear, {{capsuleName}}. Follow the LANDING checklist.
Ok, the drogue is out!
Roger. Prepare for the main.
Main is out, what a beautiful sight. Seems like the rest of the batteries held, no issues.
Yeah. Once again, you made history. This is a huge achievement! You are scheduled for two more flights.
Recovery is heading in your direction.
Roger.
This is USS Noa. We do not have a visual, yet.
Roger, Noa.
Ok, we have a visual, but we are still quite far. We estimate to be there in about 20 minutes.
Roger.
And splashdown! Sure is good to be home.
Roger, great work. That's another first for you!
I'm sure you will catch up, Patrick. Score is 2 - 0.
You bet I will! Will see you at the debrief. This is MCC signing off. [MISSION END]

Title: MISSION 3 - ATLAS
Description: After a lot of failed tests, the Mercury-Atlas launch vehicle is finally considered ready for crewed flight. Being far more powerful than the Redstone, it is capable of inserting an astronaut into orbit.
BriefingText:
Scheduled Launch Time:
02/20/1962 at 14:37:39 UTC

Mission Objectives:
- Evaluate the performance of a manned-spacecraft system in a two-orbit mission
- Evaluate the effects of spaceflight on the astronaut
- Obtain the astronaut's opinions on the operational suitability of the spacecraft systems
- Exercise and evaluate further the performance of the Mercury Worldwide Network

Details:
The Atlas launch vehicle will ignite its three engines to take the rocket through the atmosphere. After 2 minutes and 14 seconds, the booster engines will cut off, and the booster will stage. The sustainer engine will remain lit for the final part of the ascent. Upon insertion, the same procedures as with a Redstone Mission will take place.

Orbit 1:
After insertion, you will perform the Orbit Checklist, and verify core functionality of the attitude control system by tracking the launch vehicle. When reaching the coast of Africa, you will take manual control and yaw the spacecraft into a prograde attitude. You will also observe the Atlas launch vehicle (sustainer).

When reaching the Indian Ocean, you will enter the night side of Earth. At this transition, you will perform the dark side checklist, and observe the sunset.

You will cross Australia during the night. When crossing, you will observe the city lights visible. Over the Pacific, you will observe the sunrise before crossing the U.S.

Orbit 2:
You will be planning for retrograde, with a splashdown in the Atlantic.

Planned Retro MET
03 hours 03 minutes and 30 seconds.
